This project evaluates the performance of two page replacement algorithms—First-In-First-Out (FIFO) and Least Recently Used (LRU)—and compares them with the Round Robin CPU scheduling algorithm. The study focuses on measuring efficiency using metrics such as page faults, waiting time, and turnaround time. Experimental results demonstrate the trade-offs between memory management and CPU scheduling strategies, highlighting how algorithm design impacts system performance.
--------------------------
Problem Definition

Efficient resource management is a fundamental challenge in operating systems. Memory management algorithms such as FIFO and LRU determine which pages to replace when memory is full, while scheduling algorithms like Round Robin determine how CPU time is allocated among processes.

The goal of this project is to

Compare FIFO and LRU in terms of page fault frequency
Evaluate Round Robin based on waiting time and turnaround time
Analyze trade-offs between simplicity, fairness, and efficiency
--------------------------
Algorithm Explanations

First-In-First-Out (FIFO):

FIFO replaces the oldest page in memory when a new page needs to be loaded. It uses a queue-like structure where the first inserted page is the first removed.It's simple to implement, does not consider usage patterns, and can lead to inefficient replacements.

Least Recently Used (LRU):

LRU replaces the page that has not been used for the longest time. It assumes that recently used pages are more likely to be used again. It's more efficient than FIFO in most cases, requires tracking page usage, and higher overhead compared to FIFO.

Round Robin Scheduling:

Round Robin allocates CPU time in fixed time slices (quantum) and cycles through processes. It ensures fairness among processes, prevents starvation, and performance depends heavily on quantum size
--------------------------
Theoretical Complexity

Algorithm	Time Complexity	Space Complexity
FIFO = O(n)	 O(capacity)
LRU =	O(n)	 O(capacity)
Round Robin	= O(n × cycles)	 O(n)

FIFO and LRU both iterate through page references, Round Robin depends on number of cycles required to complete all processes.
