Experimental Design

The experiments were conducted using Python implementations of each algorithm.

Inputs Used:

FIFO & LRU:
Page reference string: [1, 2, 3, 1, 4, 5]
Frame capacity: 3

Round Robin:
Processes: ["P1", "P2", "P3"]
Burst times: [10, 5, 8]
Time quantum: 2

Metrics Measured:

FIFO & LRU:
Number of page faults

Round Robin:
Waiting time
Turnaround time
Average values for both
--------------------------
Results & Analysis

Page Replacement Algorithms:
FIFO produced a higher or equal number of page faults compared to LRU, LRU performed better by utilizing recent access patterns. LRU adapts to usage behavior, while FIFO blindly replaces pages, leading to inefficiencies.

Round Robin Scheduling:
Provided fair CPU allocation among all processes, it had average waiting time and turnaround time were moderate with smaller time quantum increased context switching overhead. Round Robin balances fairness and performance but requires careful tuning of the time quantum.

Overall:

FIFO: simplest but least efficient
LRU: more efficient but slightly more complex
Round Robin: ensures fairness but not directly comparable to page replacement algorithms
--------------------------
Conclusion

The study demonstrates that algorithm choice significantly impacts system performance. LRU outperforms FIFO in minimizing page faults due to its awareness of usage patterns. Round Robin, while not directly comparable, provides an effective scheduling strategy that ensures fairness among processes. Future work could explore additional algorithms and larger datasets to further validate these findings.
